      <bioghist id="aspace_e3fdb09fe2a07205336717c552b3ceec">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Thomas Clap served as the rector and first president of Yale from 1740 to 1766. Born in Scituate, Massachusetts, in 1703, he graduated from Harvard in 1722 and was installed as the minister in Windham, Connecticut, in 1725. He held that position until he accepted the rectorship of Yale, taking over from his predecessor Elisha Williams.</p>
         <p>Known for his religious orthodoxy, Clap led the establishment of a college church and was engaged in various heated theological disputes with the "Old Light" and the "New Light" Congregationalists as well as the Anglicans. Clap is remembered for enacting various reforms in college rules and discipline, for emphasizing the religious aspects of education at Yale, and for broadening the college curriculum, especially in the sciences. Under his leadership, Yale grew in size, issued a new charter in 1745 (under which the rector became the president), and built Connecticut Hall (completed in 1752). Although a strict Congregationalist, Clap's interest in and emphasis on scientific learning led to changes in Yale's curriculum. He assisted in acquiring a printing press for the city and scientific, electrical, and astronomical equipment for the college through his relationship with Benjamin Franklin. He also expanded the college's library. Among his publications is Annals or History of Yale College, published in 1766.</p>
         <p>Thomas Clap enslaved several people over the course of his life. In 1737, in his record of people in his household, he included the enslaved Pompey, born about 1713; Phillis, born about 1717; and Tamar, born on December 18, 1736. Church records show he baptized Sylva, a Black child enslaved in his household, in 1738. A 1758 advertisement in the Connecticut Gazette describes the escape of an enslaved Black man named George, enslaved by Thomas Clap. In addition, a man enslaved to Clap is listed among the workers who built Connecticut Hall; that person has not yet been identified by name.</p>
         <p>Clap resigned as president of Yale in 1766 and died in 1767.</p>
         <p>Information in this biographical note was drawn in part from <ref actuate="onrequest"
                 href="https://yaleandslavery.yale.edu/sites/default/files/2024-02/Yale%20and%20Slavery%20A%20History%20Feb2024%20David%20Blight%20with%20the%20Yale%20and%20Slavery%20Research%20Project.pdf"
                 show="new">David Blight and the Yale and Slavery Research Project, <title>
                  <part>Yale and Slavery: A History</part>
               </title>. Yale University Press, 2024</ref>.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_21255589c3fefe11ab8497da1c130299">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The records consist of correspondence, memoirs, notes, observations, and other writings of Thomas Clap concerning Yale College.</p>
         <p>Folder 7, "Account of the Cost of the New College," consists of records documenting the building of Connecticut Hall, which was completed in 1752 and is the oldest surviving building on the Yale campus. The records include documentation of workers who constructed the building, including information on work done by Jethro Luke and his son Gad Luke, both free Black men living in New Haven, and by five enslaved Black men–Dick (enslaved by Theophilus Munson), Mingo (enslaved by Archibald McNeil), Jack (enslaved by the Reverend Joseph Noyes), and a man enslaved by Thomas Clap whose name is not yet known, and another man, enslaved by a Mr. Bonticou (likely Timothy Bonticou, Sr.), whose name is not yet known.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_aa0cef7d330fd768b24c8cf0162253c0">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The records are arranged chronologically.</p>
      </arrangement>
